Historical Operations (2006–2012)

Stuxnet / Operation Olympic Games — The most famous cyberweapon in history, a joint U.S.-Israeli operation that physically destroyed ~1,000 nuclear centrifuges at Iran's Natanz facility using four zero-day exploits. It set Iran's nuclear program back by nearly two years.
Flame & Duqu — Related espionage tools that harvested intelligence, recorded audio, and mapped networks inside Iran.

2021–2024 Escalations

Cyberattacks that paralyzed Iranian gas stations nationwide
Mass breaches of Iranian government ministries (50TB+ of data stolen)
Large-scale attacks causing internet disruptions across Iran

2025–2026 Active Conflict

U.S. Cyber Command and Space Command were among the "first movers" during initial strikes against Iran, with coordinated cyber and space effects disrupting Iranian communications and sensor networks. Axios
Nearly all traffic cameras in Tehran had reportedly been compromised for years, with encrypted feeds transmitted to servers in Israel to support targeting decisions.
Iran has been under a near-total internet blackout, with nationwide connectivity running at just 4% of normal levels, and the IRGC's cyber and intelligence headquarters were among the military sites struck. Center for Strategic and International Studies
Pro-Iranian hackers claimed a significant cyberattack against U.S. medical device company Stryker, with the group Handala known for data destruction rather than financial extortion.
